natural problem:
If $x + \frac{1}{x} = 5,$ then compute the value of
\[(x - 2)^2 + \frac{25}{(x - 2)^2}.\]

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes x :: real
assumes h0 : "x + 1 / x = 5"
shows  "(x - 2) powr 2 + 25 / (x - 2) powr 2 = 11"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 If $x + \frac{1}{x} = 5,$ then compute the value of
\[(x - 2)^2 + \frac{25}{(x - 2)^2}.\] The final Answer is 11
 ### Proof
 From the equation $x + \frac{1}{x} = 5,$ $x^2 + 1 = 5x,$ so \[x^2 = 5x - 1.\]Then \[(x - 2)^2 = x^2 - 4x + 4 = (5x - 1) - 4x + 4 = x + 3.\]Hence, \begin{align} (x - 2)^2 + \frac{25}{(x - 2)^2} &= x + 3 + \frac{25}{x + 3} \\
 &= \frac{(x + 3)^2 + 25}{x + 3} \\ &= \frac{x^2 + 6x + 9 + 25}{x + 3} \\ &= \frac{(5x - 1) + 6x + 34}{x + 3} \\ &= \frac{11x + 33}{x + 3} \\ &= \boxed{11}. \end{align}
 *)

theorem
fixes x :: real
assumes h0 : "x + 1 / x = 5"
shows  "(x - 2) powr 2 + 25 / (x - 2) powr 2 = 11"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
